# Keep the GitHub presence doc in sync

`dotgithub/github-presence.md` (repo
[PyDevices/.github](https://github.com/PyDevices/.github), local clone
`dotgithub/`) is the reference doc for "how do I / where do I find X"
questions about the PyDevices org. It goes stale fast because its claims
span many sibling repos (`pydisplay`, `cmods`, `lv_bindings`, etc.), not
just the repo it lives in.

## When to update it

Whenever a change you make affects a claim in that doc, update the doc as
part of the same piece of work -- don't wait to be asked again. Triggers
include:

- Editing a `LICENSE` file in any owned repo.
- Toggling repo settings via `gh api`/`gh repo edit` (`has_wiki`,
  `has_issues`, `has_discussions`, topics, description, homepage).
- Setting the org avatar, pinned repos, or other org profile settings.
- Adding, renaming, archiving, or changing the role/Pages site of a repo.
- Changing the shared chrome (`assets/css/site.css`,
  `assets/js/theme-toggle.js`) in a way that changes what the doc describes.

## Verify before writing a claim

Don't assert org/repo state from memory or from what you *think* you just
set -- check it, e.g. `gh api repos/PyDevices/<repo> --jq '.license,
.has_wiki, .has_issues, .has_discussions'`. This caught a real bug once: a
LICENSE simplification that looked like plain MIT still showed
`NOASSERTION` on GitHub because of one extra trailing paragraph -- only
caught by re-querying the API, not by re-reading the file.

## Keep it terse

Only document things someone would actually ask "how do I / where do I
find X" about. Don't add a bullet just because a manual step was recently
completed (e.g. "avatar: set") or because the user said they'll handle
something without reminders -- if it's done or being handled, it doesn't
need a standing mention in this doc.
